text.section:
In addition to any other funds appropriated to the Department for Libraries and Archives, there shall be appropriated annually to the department out of the general expenditure fund of the State Treasury an amount sufficient to provide the following assistance to local public libraries:
The department shall first distribute to each county public library system a foundation grant based upon the county population using the last official census as follows:
Counties with a population of twenty-two thousand (22,000) or less shall receive nine thousand dollars ($9,000);
Counties with a population between twenty-two thousand one (22,001) and forty-five thousand (45,000) shall receive eight thousand dollars ($8,000); and
Counties with a population over forty-five thousand (45,000) shall receive seven thousand dollars ($7,000); and
The department shall distribute the remaining funds appropriated for this program to each county public library system, based on the county's share of the state population, at a rate of fifty-three cents ($0.53) per capita in fiscal year 1997-98 and seventy-three cents ($0.73) per capita in fiscal year 1998-99 and each year thereafter to be used for the following purposes:
Purchase, upgrading, and maintenance of the technology necessary to enable the staff and the public to have access to electronic information;
Purchase of library materials and equipment;
Maintenance and operation of bookmobiles and extension programs;
Staff training and compensation;
Building maintenance;
Debt service;
Resource-sharing;
Program development; and
All other local library needs and services; and
For counties which do not have a public library, the department shall make the foundation grant and per capita distribution to a recognized library organization for the purpose of providing or establishing countywide public library service under existing departmental guidelines.

section.section:
It is intended that the proceeds of the fund created under this subsection be used to:
Improve early childhood development;
Support lifelong learning opportunities;
Enhance economic development;
Enrich cultural resource opportunities for all Kentuckians; and
Expand adult education and adult literacy programs.
